editorialSummary.text: Intimate cafe & bakehouse with wooden furniture, plants used as decor & a book shop next door.

text.text:
A visit to this cozy yet captivating spot treated me to a delightful culinary experience. Despite its size, it offers a wonderful atmosphere for a delightful meal. What struck me the most was the impeccable taste and quality of the food.

The Madras BBQ Chicken Pizza with its thin crust was an absolute treat – the flavors were a delightful fusion that left me craving for more. Equally delightful was the Chicken Lasagna, a cheesy delight that's a must-try, even though the portion was a tad small. The Teriyaki Chicken also stood out with its mouthwatering taste, although I wished there was a bit more on the plate.

The drinks, including the Cafe Latte and Cafe Mocha, were a burst of rich, sweet, and chocolaty goodness. What made the experience even better was the attentive yet non-intrusive staff. They politely took our order and then allowed us to enjoy our time without constant interruptions.

This place is a gem for spending quality hours with friends in a cozy setting. The best part? It won't burn a hole in your pocket. The reasonable prices make it a must-visit for anyone looking for a memorable dining experience.

text.text:
Wild Garden Cafe has been a stylish and upmarket Chennai staple for a while now. I've eaten here, ever since Amethyst began operations and the cafe itself underwent several avatars to its current form.

The space remains charming, love the styling and being surrounded by all the greenery.

The most recent dinner here, my besties and me shared a burmese khauswey, green curry rice, pepperoni pizza. I had a rojapoo (Rose) G&T, which looked attractive and tasted fresh and herby.

The odd thing was giving the phone no details for some liquor permit details, which was sorta odd. I wish there was a notice about it in the menu or something, to be prepared for such invasiveness.

The Khao suey was great, as was the green curry. My friend found the pizza a tad dry.
